Seems like we venturing into the area the 'wet-brain guys' - operate out of, the pharmacologists, chemist and molecular biologist who tinker with psychoactive drugs and brain-nerve receptors-<br><br>
A TIME magazine Special Report Vol. 148 No. 14 entitled &quot;The Frontiers of Medicine,&quot; covered PTSD along the lines John and you have mentioned. The report also reflects thoughts on Fright, fight, flight that Art commended on. Its under MENTAL DISORDERS: Targeting the Brain, you may all be interested in checking it out. Try these paths:<br><br>
http://www.pathfinder.com/@@ozq3QQQAJRRKaKqK/time/frontiers/index.html<br><br>
or<br><br>
http://www.pathfinder.com/@@ozq3QQQAJRRKaKqK/time/frontiers/adisorder.html<br><br>
Among the comments made there is;<br>
 &quot;We now know that anything -- whether a drug, a war experience or a talking therapy -- changes the way nerve cells talk to each other. In the brain, hardware (physical) as well as software (chemical) is always changing.&quot; (Items in parenthesis my insertion).<br><br>
&quot;One intriguing clue surfaced recently when magnetic-resonance-imaging scans of brains of combat veterans with PTSD were compared with those of civilians who did not have the disorder. Scans of the veterans' brains showed that the right hippocampus, a crescent-shaped structure that plays a key role in memory, was slightly smaller than normal. This may indicate that war, rape or torture actually harms the brain as well as the spirit.<br><br>
Positron-emission tomography (PET) scans tell another tale. When eight PTSD victims, civilian and military, volunteered for an experiment at Massachusetts General Hospital in Boston, a PET scan revealed that an area of their brains -- the right amygdala, a small, almond-shaped structure -- was abnormally active while they were reliving traumatic memories. &quot;The amygdala is the key to the conditioned-fear response in animal studies,&quot; explains Dr. Roger Pitman, a psychiatrist at the VA Medical Center in Manchester, New Hampshire. &quot;This study shows us that traumatic memories are activating this 'hot learning center.' It may be that stress hormones burn these memories into the brain, and that is why you have World War II vets still suffering from flashbacks of Iwo Jima.&quot;<br><br>
Yet all this new knowledge has not led to a PTSD pill; unlike the other anxiety disorders, PTSD remains a hard problem to solve. Many medications relieve certain symptoms, such as insomnia, without remedying the underlying disorder. But scientists hope that current research -- for example, studies indicating that PTSD patients' memories of disturbing images can be blunted by drugs that block one type of norepinephrine receptor -- will produce a generation of medications to treat PTSD.<br><br>
Is it possible that such studies will come up with a drug that could inoculate soldiers against war shock before they go into battle, or mute the horrifying images within hours, days or weeks? &quot;The logistics would be difficult, but it could be done,&quot; says psychiatrist Dr. J. Douglas Bremner of the Veterans Affairs Medical Center in West Haven, Connecticut. &quot;Soldiers suffering from acute-stress reactions on the battlefield are often treated with Valium and other drugs. We now think that acute-stress reaction is the prelude to PTSD. It would be nice to avert PTSD by interrupting the memory-consolidation process before those traumatic memories become pathological.&quot;<br><br>
All of the above are from the TIMES article, now I wonder if prevention could have occurred by better preparation to the horrors of war (different training on the realties of the effects of napalm upon a human being, the chances of innocent civilians being killed by our response to incoming fire), perhaps it was better that we didn't know those things which made us better fighting men because we didn't know. <br><br>
It also seems that the effects of PTSD could have been further lessen  upon our return by having given the returning VN veterans the honor due warriors. Instead of the quilt trips laid upon us. Seems like the brain protects itself by changing chemically and physically. And if new medicine can now begin to treat those areas I wonder what a kind word spoken in respect and honor would have done and what it can do even today.<br>

